title: Sabrina the Teenage Witch FULL MOVIE: Friends Forever!
description:
Sabrina Spellman is turning 13 years old and receiving her first magic wand from Enchantra. As custom for all witchlings, she enrolls in the Witch Academy to learn the three principles of witchdom (to use magic wisely, be true to one's friends, and be true to one's self). Feeling inferior because she's only a half-witch, Sabrina conceals her mixed heritage and manages to become popular. Sabrina joins her new friends in making fun of Nicole Candler, a "bookworm" who doesn't fit in. When Sabrina discovers that Nicole is a half-witch like herself, the pair become good friends. Sabrina's other friends figure something is going on between Sabrina and Nicole and set out to prove that Nicole is a half-witch. They accomplish this by levitating up to a tree outside and find the half star on her hand. Sabrina visits Nicole in her dorm room and together, they begin a journey to the witches' realm in hopes of becoming full witches.

Entering the witches' realm, Sabrina and Nicole meet a witch who shows them three doors leading to three fantasy worlds. Both girls enter the first door and become mermaids. Making their way back to the realm, they try the second door and become figure skaters. After skating into a hockey net, a hockey player appears on the ice and shoots pucks into the net where both girls are. The girls throw a few pucks at the hockey player in frustration and a hockey brawl takes place. Sabrina and Nicole escape from the pile-up and exit back into the realm. They go into the third and final door where they become princesses meet two princes and begin to dance. Enchantra finds out from the witch academy the two girls are in the realm and sends two of her minions to get them.

title: Selena Gomez STARRING In Riverdale Spin-Off About Sabrina The Teenage Witch?
description:

Selena Gomez once proved to the world that she was well-equipped to take on the world of wizardry all while simultaneously conquering her teen years, but many fans are now convinced that she may be back to take on a whole new world of witchcraft.

This time around, reports are stating that Selena is set to take on the iconic role of Sabrina Spellman from the popular â€˜90s sitcom Sabrina the Teenage Witch, after news first broke that The CW is working on a â€œdarkerâ€ take of the series. And for anyone without background knowledge of the history of Sabrina, originally played by Melissa Joan Hart, the series also stems from the same Archie Comics universe as a few characters you mightâ€™ve heard about â€“ do Jughead, Betty, Archie, or Veronica ring a bell? Thatâ€™s right, the worlds in which Riverdale and Sabrina hale from completely collide, so this is likeâ€¦ a HUGE deal.

Reports that Sabrina is set to relaunch broke back in September after Buzzfeed announced that Riverdale showrunner Roberto Aguirre-Sacasa was leading the project to be called The Chilling Adventures of Sabrina. He then tweeted a photo just weeks later implying that he was casting for the roles of Sabrina and her human boyfriend Harvey, writing QUOTE, â€œPerfect project for October as the #Riverdale family expandsâ€¦â€

Naturally, Selena Gomez fans have quickly jumped to the conclusion that sheâ€™ll be resurrecting her magic powers from The Wizards of Waverly Place, along with the fact that her new blonde hair was done specifically for the role after one twitter account pointed out that she opened up about never wanting to dye her hair unless it was for a movie role. 

Other speculation as to who will be up for the part went to Disneyâ€™s Descendants star Dove Cameron when she posted a cryptic photo to Instagram of the original Sabrina cartoon series months ago. Fans jumped on the idea that Dove would be making a cameo on Riverdale in the coming seasons as witches are likely to become introduced into the storyline, but unfortunately this rumor also has no truth to it just yet. 

Many others think that Dove may be playing Sabrina Spellman on Riverdale, and Selena will be portraying Sabrina in the spinoff series, but something tells us weâ€™ve got a while until any official news is announced, because according to Agguire-Sacasa, introducing such a major character, let alone a supernatural like Sabrina, into the Riverdale plot would be tricky, and may overshadow everything else they had planned.

Regardless, it doesnâ€™t seem like the idea is completely off the table, so weâ€™re still holding out hope for Sabrina to make her grand TV return once again. But right now I gotta know all your thoughts on Selena rumored to play Sabrina, so get to talking down here in the comments, and as always, donâ€™t forget to subscribe.  In the little town of Greendale lives Sabrina Spellman, a cute twelve year-old with a big heart and an even bigger secret.  Sabrina is half mortal and half witch! The only people who know of Sabrinaâ€™s powers are her teenage witch aunts, Hilda and Zelda, her lovable mortal Uncle Quigley, her best friend Chloe and her mischievous cat, Salem.  Heâ€™s really a warlock who has been turned into a feline by the Witchesâ€™ Council as punishment for past discretions. Against her Uncle Quigleyâ€™s many warnings never to use magic to solve problems, Sabrina often â€œborrowsâ€ spells from the Spookie Jar and wreaks middle school havoc with her friend Harvey â€“ who has no clue about Sabrinaâ€™s powers. Between Sabrinaâ€™s unpredictable relatives, her wealthy and conceited arch nemesis, Gem Stone, and her hilariously miscast spells, Sabrinaâ€™s life is one big fun-filled adventure just waiting to happen!  With a touch of magic and a dish of chaos, Sabrina is sure to win your heart!

â˜…â˜†â˜… Show Info â˜…â˜†â˜…

Sabrina Spellman, a perfectly normal 16-year-old, is informed by her aunts, Hilda and Zelda, that she (and they, and her whole family on her father's side) are witches. She lives with them in Massachusetts while preparing to receive her witch's license. Along the way, she gets into many scrapes while figuring out how certain spells work. She also has to keep the secret from her boyfriend, Harvey, friends Jenny and later Valerie, stuck-up nemesis Libby, and her ever-suspicious vice-principal, Mr. Kraft.

title: Melissa Joan Hart Reflects on 'Sabrina The Teenage Witch' 20 Years Later
description: Tuesday marks the 20th anniversary of Sabrina, the Teenage Witch's TV debut. Fans fell in love with Melissa Joan Hart who played the teenager with magical powers. Since then, she went on to produce her latest show, Melissa and Joey. She also directed and produced a new feature which is currently in development. #InsideEdition

And despite everyone's efforts to cheer her, she seeks solace and solitude in an alternate world inside her mirror, where she becomes trapped in her own bad mood. In the end, she endorses Aunt Hilda's recipe for a good time - a gigantic flan.

title: Sabrina the Teenage Witch cartoon intro
description: More than 25 years before Melissa Joan Hart created the live-action role on TV, the cartoon version of "Sabrina" was a staple for those of us on Saturday mornings in the 1970s.  Sabrina Spellman was actually the cousin of Archie Andrews (of The Archies fame), and lived in a funky house with her aunts Hilda and Zelda.  Also appearing was Salem the cat, who not only spoke but actually could perform witchcraft.  This version of "Sabrina" was a lot more hipper than the Hart version, but hey, we do what we can with what we've got to work with.

title: SABRINA THE TEENAGE WITCH Reunion Panel â€“ Awesome Con 2022
description:
Sabrina the Teenage Witch stars Melissa Joan Hart, Caroline Rhea, and Beth Broderick gave a reunion panel at Awesome Con 2022 to talk about the show, their careers, and to answer fan questions.

Melissa Joan Hart was Sabrina Spellman on Sabrina the Teenage Witch, but can also be seen in Clarissa Explains It All, Drive Me Crazy, No Good Nick, Dear Christmas, Mistletoe in Montana, Melissa & Joey, and The Loud House to name a few.

Caroline Rhea played Hilda Spellman, or Aunt Hilda, on Sabrina the Teenage Witch. She has also had roles in Pride & Joy, The Suite Life of Zack & Cody, Sordid Lives: The Series, Sydney to the Max, and Phineas and Ferb among others. She also reprised her role on Chilling Adventures of Sabrina.

Beth Broderick portrayed Zelda Spellman (Aunt Zelda) in Sabrina the Teenage Witch. She has also played characters on Lost, ER, Under the Dome, Walker, Bosch, and also reprised her role on Chilling Adventures of Sabrina.

This panel was recorded on June 4th, 2022.

To learn more about Awesome Con, visit https://awesome-con.com

title: Visiting the Sabrina the Teenage Witch House/Spellman Manor | Filming Location Freehold, New Jersey
description:
#sabrinatheteenagewitch #filminglocations #thetravelingcookies #spellmanmanor

We visited a filming location from Sabrina the Teenage Witch, Spellman Manor! This house was used in the Sabrina the Teenage Witch series that ran from 1996-2003, starting on ABC's TGIF lineup and starring Melissa Joan Hart! The house is located in Freehold, NJ. Only the outside of the home was used in filming, as the inside of the home was on a soundstage. Season one was recorded at Universal Studios in California and seasons two through seven were filmed at Paramount Pictures. 

Please leave a comment down below if you have any requests of any other filming locations in New Jersey or any of the surrounding states! We would love to get there for you!

title: Britney Spears - Sabrina the teenage witch (1999) Making of
description:
The show stars Melissa Joan Hart as Sabrina Spellman, an American teenager who, on her sixteenth birthday, discovers she has magical powers. She lives with her 600-year-old aunts, witches Hilda (played by Caroline Rhea) and Zelda (played by Beth Broderick), and their magical talking cat Salem (voiced by Nick Bakay) at 133 Collins Road[2] in the fictional Boston suburb of Westbridge, Massachusetts through most of the series.

The series' first four seasons aired on ABC from September 27, 1996, to May 5, 2000; the final three seasons ran on The WB from September 22, 2000, to April 24, 2003.

title: Behind The Magic: Sabrina the Teenage Witch Reunion Interviews
description:
In this delightful best-of episode Amanda guides you through a special reunion of sorts. Melissa Joan Hart, who portrayed the lovable Sabrina Spellman, sits down with the many of the core cast members to get personal experiences, untold stories, and insider secrets that made "Sabrina the Teenage Witch" a cherished show for generations.

Relive your favorite moments from the series, laugh along with the cast's hilarious anecdotes, and gain fresh insights into the magic behind the scenes. Whether you're a long-time fan of "Sabrina the Teenage Witch" or a newcomer curious about its enduring appeal, this podcast episode is sure to cast a spell on you.

Tune in to "What Women Binge with Melissa Joan Hart - Best of Sabrina the Teenage Witch Cast Interviews" and experience the enchanting world of Sabrina Spellman like never before. It's a magical podcast journey you won't want to miss!Featured Cast Interviews:

1. Caroline Rhea (Aunt Hilda): Caroline Rhea's wit and charm have won the hearts of millions as Aunt Hilda in "Sabrina the Teenage Witch." In this interview segment, Caroline shares behind-the-scenes stories, her thoughts on Aunt Hilda's character development, and the camaraderie on set.

Sabrina Spellman
Sabrina is a half witchâ€“half mortal that won't become magically empowered until she's sixteen, but she is able to borrow spells from her aunts Hilda and Zelda using a magical "Spooky Jar", which she often does. However, she usually finds that her meddling turns situations from bad to worse. Her friend Chloe is aware of Sabrina's magic but Harvey Kinkle, another friend and her romantic interest, isn't. She is secretly in love with Harvey and wants one day to marry him.[citation needed] She wears a white tank top with a pink stripe, a green moon-shaped earring paired with a yellow star-shaped earring, pink skirt, pink hair-clips in her bangs, with white and pink sneakers. When she casts a spell the magic produced is pink and yellow. She is voiced by Emily Hart; Melissa Joan Hart's sister who played her cousin Amanda in the episode "Witchright Hall".

Harvey Kinkle
Harvey has a cute and sweet personality. While he only admits to Sabrina that she is his "best pal," he likes her very much. However, Harvey is unaware Sabrina is a witch although often sees the results of the magic himself. He is voiced by Bill Switzer.

title: Kiernan Shipka To Star In Netflix's Sabrina The Teenage Witch Reboot
description:

Mad Menâ€™s Kiernan Shipka has officially been cast as Sabrina in the upcoming Sabrina: The Teenage Witch reboot. 

Iâ€™m not even sure we can call this one a reboot, considering this is going to be a much darker Sabrina than weâ€™ve ever seen before!

Netflix has announced that Kiernan Shipka, Kiernan is best known as her role as Sally Draper in Mad Men. Kiernan wowed fans and critics alike as her turn as Jon Hamm and January Jonesâ€™s daughter in the hit AMC series, so thereâ€™s no doubt sheâ€™s ready to take on the lead of the upcoming Sabrina reboot. 

One executive producer of the show said of Kiernanâ€™s casting QUOTE, â€œWe're all such huge fans of Kiernan's work that when we started talking about who this new incarnation of Sabrina could be, her name was on everyone's wish list. This is a darker, more macabre version of Sabrina, and we're incredibly excited for people to see Kiernan make this iconic character her own.â€

And heâ€™s not kidding when he says this version of Sabrina is going to be darker. For those who were HUGE fans of the original Sabrina: The Teenage Witch series, which starred Melissa Joan Hart as the half-human, half-witch Sabrina Spellman, donâ€™t expect this reboot to be any kind of continuation of the hit 90s show--because according to the showâ€™s description, itâ€™s going to be downright scary. 

The show is being described as QUOTE, â€œtonally in the vein of Rosemary's Baby and The Exorcist," with "Sabrina wrestling to reconcile her dual natureâ€”half-witch, half-mortalâ€”while standing against the evil forces that threaten her, her family and the daylight world humans inhabit.â€ And the new Sabrina herself is also a far cry from the comedic and spunky Melissa Joan Hart version we all came to know and love in the 90s, with her character described as QUOTE, â€œAn empowered young woman, half-human, half-witch, Sabrina is just beginning her dark education as a sorceress, even as she tries to maintain a normal life as a sophomore at Baxter High. Intelligent, compassionate and brave to the point of recklessness, Sabrina is all that stands between us and the forces of darkness that threaten our world.â€

Now, if all that has you excited and ready to get your binge-watching on, then youâ€™ll be thrilled to know that Netflix has already ordered two seasons of the show. And if youâ€™re a fan of the CWâ€™s Riverdale, than you should be even MORE excited for this version of Sabrina, because it takes place in the same universe as the Riverdale comics. I donâ€™t know about you guys, but Iâ€™m already crossing my fingers for an epic cross-over episode.

Sabrina: The Animated Series is an American animated television series based on the Archie Comics character Sabrina the Teenage Witch.[1] It was produced by Savage Studios Ltd. and Hartbreak Films in association with DIC Entertainment, which was owned by Disney at the time.

The cartoon is a non-canon spin-off of the live action series that ran on ABC (also owned by Disney). In 2002, a movie, Sabrina: Friends Forever, and a spin-off series, Sabrina's Secret Life, were produced by DiC, this time without the ownership of Disney.

Unlike previous incarnations, Sabrina Spellman in this series is depicted as a 12-year-old attending middle school. As in the original comic series, Sabrina lives with her two aunts, Hilda and Zelda Spellman, and her loud-mouthed cat Salem Saberhagen, all of whom advise Sabrina on the use of magic. It is considered a spin-off of the live-action series and borrows certain elements from it, but is obviously set in an alternate universe, as it contradicts the live-action show's premise of Sabrina not knowing about magic prior to her sixteenth birthday.

Most episodes center on the typical problems of middle school, along with those that stemmed from Sabrina's inexperience with or misuse of various magic, witchcraft, and extremely powerful and complex spells. Sabrina and her best friend Chloe would often use magic (often from the "Spooky Jar"; a cookie jar containing a genie-like being in the family's kitchen) for all sorts of perceived emergencies, ranging from trying to fit into skinny new clothes to turning Sabrina's crush Harvey into a superhero. By the end of each episode, her innate magical abilities would unintentionally backfire and Sabrina would learn that using magic usually is not the solution to her day-to-day problems.

Sabrina Spellman
Sabrina is a half witchâ€“half mortal that won't become magically empowered until she's sixteen, but she is able to borrow spells from her aunts Hilda and Zelda using a magical "Spooky Jar", which she often does. However, she usually finds that her meddling turns situations from bad to worse. Her friend Chloe is aware of Sabrina's magic but Harvey Kinkle, another friend and her romantic interest, isn't. She is secretly in love with Harvey and wants one day to marry him.[citation needed] She wears a white tank top with a pink stripe, a green moon-shaped earring paired with a yellow star-shaped earring, pink skirt, pink hair-clips in her bangs, with white and pink sneakers. When she casts a spell the magic produced is pink and yellow. She is voiced by Emily Hart; Melissa Joan Hart's sister who played her cousin Amanda in the episode "Witchright Hall".

Harvey Kinkle
Harvey has a cute and sweet personality. While he only admits to Sabrina that she is his "best pal," he likes her very much. However, Harvey is unaware Sabrina is a witch although often sees the results of the magic himself. He is voiced by Bill Switzer.

title: Martin Mull, actor known for 'Clue,' 'Sabrina the Teenage Witch,' dies at 80
description:
Martin Mull, an actor known for various TV and film roles, including "Clue," "Roseanne," and "Sabrina the Teenage Witch," has died at 80. The actor's daughter confirmed the news via Instagram on Friday night.

"I am heartbroken to share that my father passed away at home on June 27th, after a valiant fight against a long illness," wrote daughter Maggie Mull. "... He was never not funny. My dad will be deeply missed by his wife and daughter, by his friends and coworkers, by fellow artists and comedians and musicians, and â€” the sign of a truly exceptional person â€” by many, many dogs."

Salem falls for a fellow feline. He learns that she is a kitty-witch as well. They fall in love and want to run off together. But Salem must decide if he wants to reverse his curse and become human again or stay with the Spellmans.

Sabrina is excited when her father drops in for a visit. Sheâ€™s disappointed to find that her father has brought along with him his fiancÃ©e. Sabrina intent on having her dad all to herself puts a spell on Futura. Instead of getting rid of her, she turns Futura into some she can relate to. Unfortunately her father doesnâ€™t feel the same way because Futura is now an obnoxious 12 year-old. Just when he is about to break off his engagement, Sabrina â€˜fesses up realizing she should have put her dadâ€™s feelings first.

Uncle Quigley decides to reinstate Family Fun Night on Saturdays evenings! Sabrina and the Aunts think that Quigley is in serious need of a love life. They set him up with Sabrinaâ€™s principal. Sabrina decides to go on the date with him to help but she only makes things. She casts a spell that makes Quigley irresistible to women. They must stop the madness thatâ€™s come over the women of Greendale, who will do anything to get a glimpse of Quigley.

Sabrina Spellman
Sabrina is a half witchâ€“half mortal that won't become magically empowered until she's sixteen, but she is able to borrow spells from her aunts Hilda and Zelda using a magical "Spooky Jar", which she often does. However, she usually finds that her meddling turns situations from bad to worse. Her friend Chloe is aware of Sabrina's magic but Harvey Kinkle, another friend and her romantic interest, isn't. She is secretly in love with Harvey and wants one day to marry him.[citation needed] She wears a white tank top with a pink stripe, a green moon-shaped earring paired with a yellow star-shaped earring, pink skirt, pink hair-clips in her bangs, with white and pink sneakers. When she casts a spell the magic produced is pink and yellow. She is voiced by Emily Hart; Melissa Joan Hart's sister who played her cousin Amanda in the episode "Witchright Hall".

title: SABRINA THE TEENAGE WITCH (1996) Cast Then and Now 2022 (26 years later) How they changed.
description:
Find out how the main characters of SABRINA THE TEENAGE WITCH, the 90s American television sitcom, are today.

Sabrina the Teenage Witch is an American television sitcom created by Nell Scovell, based on the Archie Comics series of the same name. It premiered on September 27, 1996 on ABC to over 17 million viewers in its "T.G.I.F." lineup.

It stars Melissa Joan Hart as American teenager Sabrina Spellman, who, on her 16th birthday, learns she has magical powers (a departure from the Archie Comics series, in which she has known of her powers since an early age). She lives with her 600-year-old aunts, witches Hilda (played by Caroline Rhea) and Zelda (played by Beth Broderick), and their magical talking cat Salem (voiced by Nick Bakay), at 133 Collins Road in the fictional Boston suburb of Westbridge, Massachusetts through the rest of the series.

The first four seasons aired on ABC from September 27, 1996 to May 5, 2000. The final three seasons ran on The WB from September 22, 2000 to April 24, 2003.

title: The Sims 4 - Speed Build - Spellman Manor (Sabrina The Teenage Witch)
description:
Oh dear GOD. This has taken me ALL day. I started at 11am, it is now 8:10pm and I'm only just uploading this. This may have been one of the most difficult builds I have ever done and I tell you what, I'm damn proud of it. 

This is the Spellman's house from Sabrina The Teenage Witch, the original not that new Netflix one (though I may give the Spellman Mortuary a go one day as that house is BEAUTIFUL). 

Highlight of this build, has to be Sabrina's room, I think I made a damn good copy of it, the same goes for the kitchen too!

I hope you enjoy, please like and subscribe cause I might cry if this video is a massive FLOP.

600 year old Aunt Witches Hilda and Zelda.

title: sabrina the teenage witch
description:
'what's the first rule of witch club? don't talk about witch club.'

sabrina spellman (sabrina carpenter) is sent to live with her aunt zelda (julia ormond) and aunt hilda (madchen amick) by her father edward (matt bomer). he reveals in a letter that she is a witch and her aunts are there to guide her in controlling her powers. her mother diana (dianna agron) was a mortal that passed away when she was very young. also living with them is salem saberhagen, a witch that tried to take over the world and was sentenced to 100 years as a cat and hilda's punishment for following him is to take care of him during his sentence. sabrina also has feelings for harvey kinkle (peyton meyer) but as he is mortal, their relationship has its ups and downs. being half witch, she is also thinking about attending the witch academy despite the elitism of one of the witches there, cassandra (sarah jeffery). and unbeknownst to her, her father is tracking down one of his enemies (alex pettyfer) who was responsible for her mother's death. when her father returns for her, he has brought a surprise, a half brother (logan lerman).

i watched this show back in the day and loved it. salem is one of my favorite characters ever. a remake would be great but only if done well (and if the voice actor for salem would return). i think sabrina carpenter would make a lovely sabrina. and my lucaya heart would be very pleased if peyton is the harvey. i kinda played around with the storyline from the show here and made it a bit darker, with more mystery and surprises (though salem's funny cannot be stopped). the witch academy is from the television cartoon.

title: Sabrina the Teenage Witch 1996 Cast Then and Now 2023 â˜… How They Changed
description:
Sabrina the Teenage Witch 1996 Cast Then and Now 2023 â˜… How They Changed

Sabrina the Teenage Witch is an American television sitcom created by Nell Scovell, based on the Archie Comics series of the same name. It premiered on September 27, 1996, on ABC to over 17 million viewers in its "T.G.I.F." lineup.
It stars Melissa Joan Hart as American teenager Sabrina Spellman, who, on her 16th birthday, learns she has magical powers (a departure from the Archie Comics series, in which she has known of her powers since an early age). She lives with her 600-year-old aunts, witches Hilda (played by Caroline Rhea) and Zelda (played by Beth Broderick), and their magical talking cat Salem (voiced by Nick Bakay), at 133 Collins Road in the fictional town of Westbridge, Massachusetts in the Greater Boston area.

The series aired on ABC for its first four seasons, with the final episode on the network on May 5, 2000. The final three seasons ran on The WB from September 22, 2000, to April 24, 2003.

title: Is being a witch a bad thing? - Sabrina the teenage witch
description:
https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/lets-re-watch-it-again/id1625575465?i=1000580644138
Website: https://letsrewatchitagain.buzzsprout.com

Hey y'all, today we are rewatching Sabrina the Teenage Witch, season one episode 23, The Crucible. 
Our actual teenage witch is headed town  historic Salem village to dress up as a puritan and experience life before MTV ruled the world. This episode mimics the events of a play by Arthur Miller, The Crucible. This play fictionalized actual events in the town of Salem where women were accused of witchcraft. 

Sabrina the Teenage Witch  starred Melissa Joan Hart as Sabrina Spellman, a girl who discovers on her 16th birthday that she is a witch. As a novice witch, her spells often go awry. Her witch aunts Hilda and Zelda Spellman (played by Caroline Rhea and Beth Broderick, respectively) counsel her on the proper use of her magic and give her moral advice. Additionally, Hilda and Zelda must take care of Salem Saberhagen (voiced by Nick Bakay), a witch turned into a cat for trying to take over the world. Sabrina's basic premise and loopy humor earned the show comparisons to the 1960s television series Bewitched. Like Bewitched all of our female witches have names that end with an A. 

On a class field trip to Salem, all the students at Westbridge High are told to act like townsfolk from the past, reenacting the Salem Witch Trials. When a Jealous Libby sees Jenny speaking to her latest crush, she accuses Jenny of being a witch. Sabrina steps in to defend her, only to be accused of witchcraft herself. Hilda and Zelda insist that she solve the problem on her own, prompting Sabrina to discover an odd way of doing so.

Let's Rewatch it Again!

Please rate, review, subscribe and follow everywhere you can! 

If you have any thoughts, questions, theories, or movie/episode requests send them to me on

Instagram: @LetsReWatchitAgain

description:
Comic Book Artist Tania del Rio on Sabrina the Teenage Witch
Tania del Rio - comic book artist and writer - discusses her popular run in Archie Comics' Sabrina the Teenage Witch and bringing a Manga style to the book.


â–ºâ–ºSubscribe To SYFY Wire: http://po.st/SubscribeSYFYWire
More About 'Sabrina the Teenage Witch': Sabrina the Teenage Witch is a comic book series published by Archie Comics about the adventures of a fictional American teenager named Sabrina Spellman. Sabrina was created by writer George Gladir and artist Dan DeCarlo, and first appeared in Archie's Madhouse #22 (cover-dated Oct. 1962). The series' premise is that Sabrina, a "half-witch" â€“ her mother is an ordinary human, or "mortal" as witches refer to them, while her father is a witch â€“ lives with her two aunts, Hilda and Zelda Spellman, both witches themselves, in the fictional town of Greendale, which is located somewhere near Riverdale, the home of Archie Andrews. Also living with the three women as the family pet is Salem Saberhagen, a witch who's been turned into a cat as punishment for world domination attempts.

SYFY WIRE is dedicated to all things science fiction, fantasy and supernatural horror (with some other stuff like space and future technology thrown in for good measure). It features news and original reporting about movies, TV, games, books, genre figures and more. Weâ€™ve got recaps, interviews, movie trailers, and sneak peeks at upcoming TV shows. title: The Cast of Sabrina the Teenage Witch Says Hello to Me at 90s Con
description:
Attending 90s Con in Hartford to celebrate my 30th birthday marked the beginning of a more optimistic spring and summer. Now that it's coming to a close, I'm thrilled to share a compilation of clips I requested some of the cast members of Sabrina The Teenage Witch to record with me. To be honest, speaking with them felt like I was meeting extended family.

Nate Richert gave me some of the warmest, tightest hugs when I approached him at his table. The first thing I told him was that he hasn't changed a bit and it made my day to see him flattered. He was chill and grounded like his character, Harvey and it was a wonder why I gathered he was still the same guy he portrayed twenty-eight years ago. Getting our photos taken was just as fun because it was a rare opportunity where I can make faces and not cringe about it afterwards.

Jenna Green was a lively, friendly individual that I have to thank for putting up with me when I requested to recreate a part in the pancake episode that was stuck in my head except instead of a pancake, I had a used gift card as a substitute. The line at her table wasn't too long so there was thankfully time to make that happen.

Melissa Joan Hart was a charitable philanthropist that has grown to be an older, wiser version of Sabrina by the time it was my turn to meet her. Since she was a more popular actress, her table was packed so the interaction was short but special. I passed the time by interacting with another fan that worked in retail and that helped calmed my nerves as the line was slowly moving. I read later that Melissa is a gun control advocate and she helped kindergarteners that were fleeing from a school shooting that took place in Nashville in 2023. That got me to respect her more. ^_^

The Episode I Had On My Mind When I Was At the Con; ðŸ˜†

title: Sabrina The Teenage Witch (1970) - Mis-Guided Tour - Correct Video Speed (High Bitrate SD)
description:
my server - https://discord.gg/4CbPdX4XFZ yell at me on Discord if I did something wrong, username - ahdollaryt





Re-rendered and optimized for high-definition (from interlaced to progressive), and subsequently re-optimized for video streaming, with none of the half-retarded interlacing artifacts that all the other uploads seem to have.


This is Season 1, Episode 19a, originally released under "Sabrina and the Groovie Goolies" in 1970 directed by Hal Sutherland and produced by Norm Prescott and Lou Scheimer, slowed down to match the original NTSC speed, pitch, and 60Hz frequency to correct the common habit Hallmark Cards had of speeding up Filmation's materials throughout the late 1990s and early 2000s for PAL home media releases, this would then be followed up by Hallmark discarding the original film negatives and sound masters (the currently missing Comedy Hour music segments were most likely long gone by this time, they didn't show up on Archie/Sabrina content after syndication in 1976, that or they were cut from the NTSC videotape reels for other reasons), something that wasn't known (but suspected) until after Entertainment Rights' acquisition of Filmation's materials in 2004.


Hexter shows up again when Sabrina is meant to be at the local museum (at this point, I assume that Miss Della is either aware of Hexter's behavior, or tells him to cause trouble, and sends him to Sabrina on days she's planning to go out with her friends to mess with her) and causes the usual round of trouble, which eventually causes Miss Grundy, the chaperone, to go crazy and start acting like a monkey on the top of a totem pole outside the museum. At the end of the day, when Sabrina think's she's done with babysitting, some specter triplets pop up to fill her schedule, making her go crazy as well. The scene of her bouncing out of the house was included in my "Remember The Ls" video back in February 2022 (sorry this took so long to upload).


This episode has been included on the following home media releases: Sabrina the Teenage Witch: The Complete Animated Series DVD boxset 2008 (Genius Products), and Sabrina the Teenage Witch: The Complete Animated Series DVD boxset 2017 (Universal).


Interlaced videos on my channel are de-interlaced and upscaled with the software Handbrake. DVD and Blu-ray files start off as mkv, via the MakeMKV software, television captures start off as mts and are captured onto a USB flash drive through an Ematic DVR converter box. In the "Save As" portion, the file type may be changed from m4v to mp4 for post-production (if your editing software can handle m4v, or if you're uploading straight to YouTube, you can leave it alone). There, you can select "Browse" and determine where the finished product will go. If the video has some edge-matting, it'll be cropped out automatically, otherwise, it can be cropped manually by selecting "custom" on the orientation and cropping tool, then cropped in increments of two with the up and down arrows. You may select "preview" on the top of the software to help with this. In resolution and scaling, anamorphic is left on automatic, "allow upscaling" selected (1080 by default), "optimal size" de-selected, and left and right dimensions can be adjusted according to whatever aspect ratio the video will be in. 1440x1080 4:3, 1920x1080 16:9. If any cropping was done, the software will automatically scale the dimensions to match. Decomb de-interlacing filter and Bob preset are used to separate the two fields in a frame and double the frame count. Yadif/Bob can also be used. Frame rate (set to constant) is double of whatever the video started off as, according to the picture format used. PAL 25 FPS becomes 50, NTSC 29.97 FPS into 59.94. Average bitrate set to 40,000 Kbps for 4:3 video, 45,000 Kbps for 16:9 (with two-pass encoding and turbo fast-pass disabled). If you don't have a good computer, or have limited storage space, the bitrate may be lowered to something more manageable, as low as around 20,000 Kbps for 1080p video. Encoder level set to 4.1. The audio settings are the most variable part, with several bitrates and codecs to choose from in mono, stereo, and surround, as well as in different languages. For this, you can open the drop-down window on the sound options to see what's included, choose one, and copy the information over in the next few drop-downs, remembering that DVD and Blu-ray audio have a sample rate of 48 kHz. You may downsample as needed. Sometimes in the "codec" window, it'll allow you to select "(x) Passthru" which will transfer the audio automatically if you're lazy. You may also decrease the gain if you feel it's too loud, or increase it if it's not loud enough. More than likely, you'll be sending the media through post-production, where you can adjust the gain with greater precision, so this can be left alone. If you want more audio options to be added, open the "Tracks" window, select "add new track", and adjust the new track to taste.

description:
my server - https://discord.gg/4CbPdX4XFZ yell at me on Discord if I did something wrong, username - ahdollaryt





Re-rendered and optimized for high-definition (from interlaced to progressive), and subsequently re-optimized for video streaming, with none of the half-retarded interlacing artifacts that all the other uploads seem to have.


This is Season 1, Episode 26a, originally released under "Sabrina and the Groovie Goolies" in 1970 directed by Hal Sutherland and produced by Norm Prescott and Lou Scheimer, slowed down to match the original NTSC speed, pitch, and 60Hz frequency to correct the common habit Hallmark Cards had of speeding up Filmation's materials throughout the late 1990s and early 2000s for PAL home media releases, this would then be followed up by Hallmark discarding the original film negatives and sound masters (the currently missing Comedy Hour music segments were most likely long gone by this time, they didn't show up on Archie/Sabrina content after syndication in 1976, that or they were cut from the NTSC videotape reels for other reasons), something that wasn't known (but suspected) until after Entertainment Rights' acquisition of Filmation's materials in 2004.


A new trend started in Riverdale of girls getting amulets from their favorite guys, and Big Ethel gets left in the dust with Jughead not getting her one. Sabrina tries to manipulate him to a jewelry store, but he gets kicked out. She then consults Cousin Ambrose, who gives her an amulet that can change people into animals, something he only remembered on his way back to the nether. When she gives it to Ethel to make Jughead jealous, he gets smart with her, and she goes off on how uptight he is, turning him into various animals. Going back to human from a clam, Jughead gets a pearl that Ethel gawks over, and they make up, and he turns into a monkey, which Sabrina doesn't bother to undo.

description:
Fall 1996 ABC new series & season promos recorded on VHS during The Beatles Anthology Parts 1-3 via Cleveland ABC WEWS Channel 5 on 8/31/96, 9/5/96, and 9/7/96.

Promos include:

Sabrina The Teenage Witch #1 - New Series Premiere
Sabrina The Teenage Witch #2 - New Series Premiere
Sabrina The Teenage Witch #3 - New Series Premiere
Home Improvement - Season Premiere
Spin City #1 - New Series Premiere
Spin City #2 - New Series Premiere
Spin City #3 - New Series Premiere
Clueless - New Series Premiere
Roseanne - Season Premiere

Life's Work #2 - New Series Premiere
Life's Work #3 - New Series Premiere

Some info about each series, courtesy Wikipedia:

Sabrina the Teenage Witch is an American television sitcom created by Nell Scovell, based on the Archie Comics series of the same name. It premiered on September 27, 1996, on ABC to over 17 million viewers in its "T.G.I.F." lineup. It stars Melissa Joan Hart as American teenager Sabrina Spellman, who, on her 16th birthday, learns she has magical powers (a departure from the Archie Comics series, in which she has known of her powers since an early age).

Home Improvement is an American television sitcom starring Tim Allen that aired on ABC from September 17, 1991, to May 25, 1999, with a total of 204 half-hour episodes spanning eight seasons. 

Spin City is an American sitcom television series that aired from September 17, 1996, to April 30, 2002, on ABC. Created by Gary David Goldberg and Bill Lawrence, the show is set in a fictionalized version of the New York City mayor's office, and originally starred Michael J. Fox as Mike Flaherty, the Deputy Mayor of New York. Fox departed in 2000 at the conclusion of Season 4 due to symptoms of Parkinson's disease, and Charlie Sheen became the new lead as Charlie Crawford for the final two seasons. The series was cancelled after six seasons in May 2002.

Clueless is an American teen sitcom based on the 1995 film of the same name (which was inspired by Jane Austen's 1815 novel Emma). It premiered on ABC on September 20, 1996, as a part of the TGIF lineup during its first season. The series then spent its last two seasons on UPN, ending on May 25, 1999. Alicia Silverstone had a development deal with Columbia-TriStar at this time, and did not reprise her role from the film.

Roseanne is an American television sitcom created by Matt Williams which aired on ABC from October 18, 1988, to May 20, 1997, and briefly revived from March 27, 2018, to May 22, 2018. The show stars Roseanne Barr as Roseanne Conner and revolves around her family in the fictional town of Lanford, Illinois.

Life's Work is an American sitcom series that aired from September 1996 to June 1997 on ABC; the show stars Lisa Ann Walter as Lisa Ann Minardi Hunter, an assistant district attorney in Baltimore.

Townies is an American television sitcom that aired on ABC from September 18 to December 4, 1996. Created by Matthew Carlson, the series stars Molly Ringwald, Jenna Elfman, and Lauren Graham.

Common Law is an American television sitcom that premiered on ABC on September 28, 1996. The show stars Megyn Price and Greg Giraldo as a Latino lawyer at a mostly white law firm. Due to low ratings, the series was pulled from ABC's schedule after four episodes had aired.

Ellen is an American television sitcom that aired on ABC from March 29, 1994, to July 22, 1998, consisting of 109 episodes. Ellen DeGeneres stars as the title character of Ellen Morgan, a neurotic bookstore owner in her thirties.

Relativity is an American drama television series which followed a twenty-something couple, Isabel Lukens (played by Kimberly Williams) and Leo Roth (played by David Conrad), and the lives and loves of their friends and siblings in Los Angeles. The short-lived ABC series was the product of thirtysomething producers Edward Zwick and Marshall Herskovitz.

American actor and comedian Martin Mull, known for his work on the TV sitcoms Sabrina the Teenage Witch and Roseanne, has died at age 80.
Mull, who also starred in the 1985 comedy film Clue, died on Thursday at his home after a â€œvaliant fight against a long illnessâ€, his daughter, Maggie Mull, said on social media.
In a tribute on Instagram, Ms Mull wrote that her father â€œwas known for excelling at every creative discipline imaginable and for doing Red Roof Inn commercials".
â€œHe would find that joke funny,â€ she added. â€œHe was never not funny.â€
Mullâ€™s first notable role was in 1976, playing Garth Gimble on the soap opera spoof Mary Hartman, Mary Hartman, which led to two additional spin-off roles, including in the series Fernwood 2 Night.
He then landed the role of army officer Colonel Mustard in the black-comedy film Clue, inspired by the board game of the same name.
Around that time, he also began voicing the Red Roof Inn advertisements that his daughter mentioned in her tribute.
Television aficionados of the 1990s will recognise Mull from his work on Roseanne, where he played the titular characterâ€™s boss Leon Carp, or in Sabrina the Teenage Witch, where he played Principal Willard Kraft.
Mull also appeared on the critically acclaimed satirical sitcom Arrested Development, playing hapless private detective Gene Parmesan.
He guest starred in numerous other well-known television shows, including The Simpsons, Family Guy, Law and Order: Special Victims Unit, The Golden Girls and Two and a Half Men.
Mull was nominated for a Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actor in a Comedy Series for a four-episode appearance he made on HBOâ€™s political satire Veep in 2016.
Born in Chicago to an actress and a carpenter, Mull began his show business career as a songwriter and became known as a musical comedian. He opened for Frank Zappa and Bruce Springsteen at numerous live gigs in the early 1970s.
He also studied painting and graduated in 1965 from the Rhode Island School of Design with a Bachelor of Fine Arts.
In a 2013 interview with the A.V. Club, he said of his acting career that â€œevery painter I know has a day job. Theyâ€™re either teaching art at some college or driving a cabâ€.
â€œI just happened to luck into a day job thatâ€™s extraordinary and a lot of fun and buys a lot of paint,â€ he said.
As well as his daughter, Maggie, a TV writer, he leaves his wife, Wendy Haas, an actor and composer whom he wed in 1982.

description:
1990's Sitcoms all went to Disney World, especially Sabrina the Teenage Witch in 1998 to Disney's Animal Kingdom. Season 2 Episode 23 of Sabrina the Teenage Witch titled "Disney World" aired on ABC on April 24, 1998. The episode aired only 2 days after Disney's Animal Kingdom opened on April 22, 1998. We go to all the filming locations at Disney's Animal Kingdom and Disney's Coronado Springs Resort that was shown in the Sabrina the Teenage Witch episode.  The Tree of Life, Kilimanjaro Safari, Dino Land's Bone Yard, Coronado Springs Resort Rooms, and more are shown in this video. Make sure to check out when we did two Full House Filming on Locations at Disney World Videos during our 2019 25 Days of Disney. title: Former Sabrina the Teenage Witch House from 90â€™s Sitcom: 64 E Main St, Freehold NJ
description:
Former Sabrina the Teenage Witch House from 90â€™s Sitcom: Immaculately Restored Office Buildings with Vintage Charm in Prime Freehold Boro Location

Discover an extraordinary opportunity to own two exquisitely renovated office buildings that seamlessly blend vintage charm with modern convenience. Situated on E Main Street, just moments away from the bustling heart of Freehold Boro's business district, this offering presents two move-in ready properties, currently zoned for commercial/office use, accompanied by ample parking facilities.

Front Building: Spanning an expansive 4,862 square feet, this structure encompasses three meticulously finished floors and a spacious attic awaiting your creative vision. Inside, a fully equipped kitchen, numerous generously sized offices, and a delightful wraparound front porch await. Four distinct entrance doors ensure effortless access to various office spaces, enhancing efficiency and convenience.

Back Building: Nestled at the rear of the property, this building offers approximately 2,000 square feet across two levels. Featuring a functional kitchen, around five offices, and two bathrooms, it caters to a diverse range of professional needs. Currently rented to an accounting firm for $3,250 lease is up in June 2024. 

Both buildings have undergone extensive remodeling while preserving the nostalgic allure that Freehold Boro is famed for. Impeccable renovations include new roofing, flooring, plumbing, electrical systems, decking, and hardy boy siding, ensuring a turnkey experience for the prospective owner.

The front building, previously leased for $9,750, boasts enchanting period details such as intricate windows, stained glass elements, and the iconic domed turret. Furthermore, this property holds a place in pop culture history, serving as the exterior backdrop for the fictional Spellman Manor in the beloved '90s sitcom, "Sabrina the Teenage Witch."

This exceptional offering also provides versatile zoning opportunities. While presently designated for commercial and professional purposes, the property's original residential origins allow for potential conversion to a residential or mixed-use setup. Achieving this transformation necessitates a variance, a process that the zoning department estimates will take approximately three months. Interested parties are encouraged to explore this possibility through the Freehold Township zoning office. The seller is open to negotiating a credit to facilitate the variance process.

Highlighted by its feature in various prominent media outlets, including nj.com, People Magazine, Fox Business, and the Asbury Park Press, this property's distinct character and flexible potential position it as an outstanding investment opportunity.

Seize the chance to become part of Freehold Boro's storied history and thriving business environment. Contact us today to see this meticulously restored Victorian gem.

title: What the Characters from â€œSabrina the Teenage Witchâ€ Are Up to Today
description:
What the Characters from â€œSabrina the Teenage Witchâ€ Are Up to Today
Sabrina, the Teenage Witch, was one of the best-known television series of the second half of the 90s and early 2000s. It was watched by millions of teenagers around the world. More than 25 years have passed since the release of the first episode, so we invite you to succumb to nostalgia and discover how the lives of the actors of this series have developed since its end.

1. Melissa Joan Hart (Sabrina Spellman)

title: Former Sabrina the Teenage Witch House from 90â€™s Sitcom: $1,400,000 (short version)
description:
Former Sabrina the Teenage Witch House from 90â€™s Sitcom: Immaculately Restored Office Buildings with Vintage Charm in Prime Freehold Boro Location

Discover an extraordinary opportunity to own two exquisitely renovated office buildings that seamlessly blend vintage charm with modern convenience. Situated on E Main Street, just moments away from the bustling heart of Freehold Boro's business district, this offering presents two move-in ready properties, currently zoned for commercial/office use, accompanied by ample parking facilities.

Front Building: Spanning an expansive 4,862 square feet, this structure encompasses three meticulously finished floors and a spacious attic awaiting your creative vision. Inside, a fully equipped kitchen, numerous generously sized offices, and a delightful wraparound front porch await. Four distinct entrance doors ensure effortless access to various office spaces, enhancing efficiency and convenience.

Back Building: Nestled at the rear of the property, this building offers approximately 2,000 square feet across two levels. Featuring a functional kitchen, around five offices, and two bathrooms, it caters to a diverse range of professional needs. Currently rented to an accounting firm for $3,250 lease is up in June 2024. 

Both buildings have undergone extensive remodeling while preserving the nostalgic allure that Freehold Boro is famed for. Impeccable renovations include new roofing, flooring, plumbing, electrical systems, decking, and hardy boy siding, ensuring a turnkey experience for the prospective owner.

The front building, previously leased for $9,750, boasts enchanting period details such as intricate windows, stained glass elements, and the iconic domed turret. Furthermore, this property holds a place in pop culture history, serving as the exterior backdrop for the fictional Spellman Manor in the beloved '90s sitcom, "Sabrina the Teenage Witch."

This exceptional offering also provides versatile zoning opportunities. While presently designated for commercial and professional purposes, the property's original residential origins allow for potential conversion to a residential or mixed-use setup. Achieving this transformation necessitates a variance, a process that the zoning department estimates will take approximately three months. Interested parties are encouraged to explore this possibility through the Freehold Township zoning office. The seller is open to negotiating a credit to facilitate the variance process.

Highlighted by its feature in various prominent media outlets, including nj.com, People Magazine, Fox Business, and the Asbury Park Press, this property's distinct character and flexible potential position it as an outstanding investment opportunity.

Seize the chance to become part of Freehold Boro's storied history and thriving business environment. Contact us today to see this meticulously restored Victorian gem.
